[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(9-11) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "She said unto the men, I know that the Lord hath given you the land. . . .—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The words of this confession are memorable in everyway. Note the fulfilment of the prophetic song of Moses, which is partly repeated here (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 15:15-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 2:9-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), “All the inhabitants of Canaan shall melt away; fear and dread shall fall upon them.” But especially observe the expression of Rahab’s own belief, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "“",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Jehovah, your God, He is God in heaven above and in earth beneath.” Did the faith of the men of Israel go much further than this? Did it always go so far? (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 24:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 18:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jonah 1:9-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The prophets themselves could not assert much more. The greatest of them were satisfied if they could bring the people of Israel to acknowledge this. Rahab’s confession is also one of a series. The Egyptians, Philistines, Syrians, Assyrians, Babylonians, Persians, were all in turn brought to the same acknowledgment by their contact with Israel. The reason is stated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 4:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “That all the people of the earth may know the hand of Jehovah, that it is mighty.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
